\f2\b Honest Model Evaluation
\f0\b0 \
What it does well: the model is elegant and tractable. It generates a clean likelihood function despite multiple equilibria by mapping parameter regions to unique Perfect Bayesian Equilibria. The decomposition of the treatment effect into belief vs. monitoring cost channels is a genuine contribution \'97 this is exactly the kind of structural value-added that justifies going beyond reduced form.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 The limitations, which are your research opportunities:
\f0\b0 \

\f2\b First and most important: the model cannot separate belief correction from salience.
\f0\b0  The treatment simultaneously delivers more accurate information AND delivers it via a more salient, personalized channel. Bergman acknowledges this \'97 the reduction in monitoring costs (m) and the shift in beliefs (\uc0\u960 ) are estimated jointly from the same treatment arm. There is no variation that holds information content fixed while varying the channel, so the model cannot tell you whether m falls because parents literally have lower costs of verifying information, or because the WhatsApp-style message makes the problem salient enough that they act on information they already had. This is your CF2. His model has no salience parameter \'97 it's not that he estimates it at zero, it's that the object doesn't exist in his framework.\

\f2\b Second: the child is modeled as strategically hiding information, but not as responding to monitoring directly.
\f0\b0  The child in Bergman's model decides whether to disclose a verifiable report. What the model does not have is a child who adjusts effort in response to the intensity of parental monitoring per se \'97 the child's effort choice is driven by the cost parameters cH, cL and the punishment w, not by a dynamic response to being watched more closely. This means the model cannot speak to what happens when monitoring increases continuously \'97 only to discrete disclosure decisions. In your setting, where messages arrive frequently, the child's behavioral response to surveillance is a first-order issue.\

\f2\b Third: parents have biased priors (\uc0\u960  is mis-calibrated) but update rationally given the signal.
\f0\b0  Bergman finds \uc0\u960  = 0.633 in the control group (parents think 63% of kids are high type) vs 0.270 in the treatment group. This is just the cross-sectional difference in estimated priors between arms \'97 it's not a model of how beliefs update dynamically in response to signals. There is no Bayesian updating equation in the model. This means the model is silent on how quickly beliefs adjust, whether they decay between messages, and what happens when the information stream stops. Your project is fundamentally about the dynamics of belief updating \'97 which his model cannot address.\

\f2\b Fourth: the school is completely passive.
\f0\b0  R, the probability of a verifiable report existing, is a parameter \'97 it's not a choice by the school. The school does not respond strategically to the information environment. This is both a limitation and your IO contribution.\

\f2\b Fifth: the model is static.
\f0\b0  One period. No dynamics. This matters because your intervention is about changing the frequency of an information flow, and the interesting questions \'97 does the effect decay, do beliefs persist, what is the long-run impact \'97 are inherently dynamic.\
