\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 Why Go Beyond This Model: The Precise Argument
\f0\b0 \
Bergman's model answers: 
\f1\i given a treatment that simultaneously changes beliefs, monitoring costs, and reporting, how much of the effect on child effort comes from each?
\f0\i0  That's a good question and he answers it credibly.\
Your model needs to answer: 
\f1\i what is the causal effect of belief correction alone, holding the salience of the information channel fixed?
\f0\i0  And separately: 
\f1\i what is the effect of salience alone, holding information content fixed?
\f0\i0  These are different questions and they require a different model \'97 one where the salience of the signal enters the belief-updating equation as a structural parameter, not bundled into monitoring costs.\
The specific departure is this. In Bergman, when a parent receives a message, they update \uc0\u960  and their monitoring cost m changes. In your model, you would write the belief-updating equation explicitly as:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\i \cf0 New belief = f(prior belief, signal content, salience weight)
\f0\i0 \
The salience weight \uc0\u955  is a structural parameter that varies by treatment arm. If you have an arm where the information content is identical to the control but delivered via WhatsApp (your CF2 arm), you can identify \u955  directly \'97 any behavioral change in that arm, holding information constant, is the salience parameter at work. If you have an arm where information content improves but the channel stays the same as control, the residual after accounting for \u955  is the pure belief-correction effect.\
This gives you a model that is strictly richer than Bergman's, answers questions his model cannot, and is identified off variation that he did not have but that you can design into your experiment. That is a complete argument for why this is a next paper rather than a replication.\
Bergman is your main citation for parts a, b, and c. His paper establishes the puzzle (information frictions matter), the standard mechanism (belief correction), and leaves open the behavioral question (salience, channel effects, dynamic updating). His model is your explicit departure point for part d. You write: "I depart from Bergman's persuasion game by adding a salience parameter to the belief-updating equation and designing a multi-arm experiment that separately identifies belief correction from channel salience." That one sentence, with the model sketch behind it, is your answer to part d and the bonus model question.//\
Also, should I add a school dimension to this? I think a good plan is the following: 
\f2\b Core project:
\f0\b0  Static structural model with biased priors and salience parameter, identified off multi-arm RCT. This solves CF2. This is the paper you can credibly promise to deliver.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Extension 1:
\f0\b0  Add the school strategic response as a second structural layer. Same RCT data, within-classroom variation as identification, model the teacher objective function. This is the IO contribution. You frame this as a natural second paper from the same data.\

\f2\b Extension 2:
\f0\b0  Two-period model of belief persistence. What happens when the intervention stops? Do corrected beliefs persist? This uses the followup data you collect anyway. Framed as a third paper or a rich section of the second.\
Open with the puzzle \'97 information treatments work but nobody knows why. State that the mechanism question is not just scientifically interesting but policy-critical, because the optimal information policy looks completely different depending on whether the effect is belief correction, salience, child monitoring, or school response. Frame the structural model as the only tool that can answer this. Present the RCT design as purpose-built to give the model identification. Then lay out the research agenda: paper one solves the household side, paper two adds the school side, and together they give the first complete structural account of how information treatments work in education.\
The argument has three steps and you should state all three explicitly.\
Step one: information treatments are being scaled globally right now, with billions of dollars of investment, without understanding the mechanism. Cite specific programs \'97 the Brazilian and Chilean WhatsApp interventions, the SMS programs in Sub-Saharan Africa, the parent engagement platforms in US urban districts.\
Step two: without mechanism knowledge, scale-up predictions are unreliable. The effect at scale could be larger than the pilot (if the pilot undersampled high-bias parents), smaller (if general equilibrium school responses dampen the effect), or zero (if salience habituates). A policymaker cannot choose between these scenarios without a structural model.\
Step three: your research program provides exactly this. The RCT identifies the structural parameters. The model uses those parameters to compute the effect under any counterfactual policy \'97 including universal adoption, different frequencies, different channels, and different school quality contexts. This is what external validity looks like when you take it seriously.\
A lot of it is about this intuition of going large and understanding in more broad way information treatments.\
