\cf0 \strokec2 These are two theory papers that can help with the structural model...---\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 Bordalo, Gennaioli & Shleifer (BGS) \'97 Salience Theory of Choice Under Risk
\f0\b0 \
The core contribution here is that agents don't weight outcomes by their objective probabilities \'97 they overweight 
\f1\i salient
\f0\i0  states, where salience is defined by how much a payoff 
\f1\i contrasts
\f0\i0  with the available alternatives. This is context-dependent: the same information triggers different attention depending on what surrounds it.\
The translation to your setting is direct and powerful. In Bergman's model, when a parent receives a message, beliefs update and monitoring costs fall \'97 but there is no mechanism governing 
\f1\i which
\f0\i0  piece of information about child performance the parent actually focuses on. BGS gives you that mechanism. A WhatsApp message arriving on a Tuesday afternoon creates a specific context: it makes the child's missing assignments 
\f1\i contrast
\f0\i0  sharply with the parent's background model of "my kid is probably doing fine." That contrast is what drives salience, and salience is what drives the decision weight the parent attaches to the information. The standard report card fails not because it contains less information, but because it arrives in a low-contrast context \'97 surrounded by other dense school bureaucracy \'97 so the bad news is not salient.\
More specifically, BGS gives you a formal foundation for your \uc0\u955  parameter. Rather than just writing "new belief = f(prior, signal, salience weight \u955 )" as a reduced-form claim, you can now ground \u955  in a proper salience function \u963 (x
\f1\i i, x
\f0\i0 \{-i\}) where the contrast is between the performance signal and the parent's prior expectation. This makes your model structurally richer: \uc0\u955  is not a free parameter you estimate, it is derived from the contrast between signal content and prior, which you can manipulate experimentally by varying how the message is framed. A message that says "your child missed 7 assignments this week" is more salient to an overoptimistic parent than to a well-calibrated one, because the contrast with their prior is larger. This generates a testable interaction: 
\f2\b the salience effect should be stronger for parents with more biased priors
\f0\b0 , which is exactly the heterogeneity you care about for SES effects.\
There is also a subtler BGS insight that maps onto your setting. They show that diminishing sensitivity means salience falls as the absolute level of payoffs increases \'97 extreme departures from zero are less salient in proportional terms. The analogy in your context: a parent who already knows their child is struggling will find a "3 missing assignments" message less salient than a parent who believed everything was fine. This gives you a prediction about 
\f1\i habituation
\f0\i0  \'97 repeated messages may lose salience over time as the contrast with the prior shrinks, which directly addresses the decay question in your dynamic extension.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 Gabaix \'97 Sparse Max
\f0\b0 \
This paper is a different but complementary angle. Where BGS is about what draws attention within a given choice problem, Gabaix is about which 
\f1\i variables
\f0\i0  the agent includes in their model of the world at all. The sparse agent builds a simplified model, attending only to variables whose impact on their decision exceeds a threshold. Variables below that threshold are set to their default value \'97 typically the agent's prior expectation.\
In your setting, the sparse max maps onto the following question: does a parent include "child's current school performance" as an active variable in their decision-making model, or do they default to their prior? Without an information treatment, most parents \'97 especially low-SES parents facing high cognitive load \'97 will run on the default, meaning they never actively consider the signal even when it is technically available via report cards. The information treatment, particularly a high-salience WhatsApp message, effectively 
\f1\i lowers the attention cost
\f0\i0  of including child performance as an active variable, crossing the threshold in Gabaix's attention function A.\
This is useful for your model in two ways. First, it gives you a foundation for why the 
\f1\i channel
\f0\i0  matters independently of content. A report card does not lower the attention cost enough to bring child performance into the parent's active model; a personalized phone notification does. Second, the sparse max predicts that attention is allocated purposefully toward variables with high variance and high decision-relevance. This means your treatment effect should be larger for parents whose child's performance is 
\f1\i more volatile
\f0\i0  or 
\f1\i more surprising
\f0\i0  \'97 another testable prediction you can take to the data.\
The sparse max also connects to your SES heterogeneity finding from Dizon-Ross and Bergman. Gabaix's model predicts that cognitive load \'97 captured by the cost parameter \uc0\u954  \'97 raises the attention threshold, so high-load parents (low-SES, multiple children, work stress) will have a higher bar for bringing any new variable into their active model. The information treatment works by lowering the effective cost of attention, and it will have a larger impact on parents who were previously just below the threshold. This is not just a story about "poor people have less information" \'97 it is a precise structural claim about where in the attention cost distribution your treatment has bite.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
