\f2\b \cf0 \strokec2 How They Fit Together in Your Model
\f0\b0 \
The two papers are not redundant \'97 they operate at different levels. Gabaix tells you 
\f1\i whether
\f0\i0  the parent's attention is directed to child performance at all. BGS tells you 
\f1\i how
\f0\i0  that attention is weighted once it is directed. In your structural model, you need both: a first stage where the information treatment crosses the Gabaix attention threshold, and a second stage where the salience of the specific signal content \'97 governed by BGS contrast \'97 determines how much the parent's belief updates and how strongly they act.\
Concretely, your belief-updating equation becomes:\

\f2\b New belief = prior + A(\uc0\u954 , signal variance) \'d7 \u963 (signal content, prior) \'d7 (signal \u8722  prior)
\f0\b0 \
where A is Gabaix's attention function (does the parent engage at all?) and \uc0\u963  is BGS's salience function (given engagement, how much does the signal move beliefs?). Your RCT arms identify these separately: an arm that changes channel but not content identifies A, an arm that changes content but not channel identifies \u963 , and your full treatment arm identifies the joint effect.\
This is a genuine theoretical contribution beyond Bergman, and you can state it precisely: Bergman's model has neither A nor \uc0\u963  \'97 it bundles both into a single monitoring cost parameter m, which is why it cannot distinguish the channel effect from the content effect. Your model unpacks that bundle using two well-established theoretical tools from the behavioral literature. --> maybe ambition can backfire. so watchout and simplify if needed.\
