\f2\b \cf0 The concrete borrowing plan
\f0\b0 \
For the extension, I would suggest the following. Keep the production function from Fu & Mehta almost verbatim, but drop the peer quality terms (since tracking regime is not your intervention) and add the information environment as a shifter of parental beliefs and effort. Keep their school objective but add the parental monitoring disutility term. Keep their timing structure. Estimate the school-side parameters off within-classroom variation in your RCT \'97 specifically, if teachers in treatment classrooms systematically adjust their grading, homework assignments, or parent contact patterns compared to control classrooms, that variation identifies \uc0\u948 .\
The key counterfactual you can then run \'97 which Fu & Mehta cannot \'97 is: what is the equilibrium effect of universal information provision, accounting for both the household-side belief correction and the school-side strategic response? If \uc0\u948  is large and positive (schools strongly dislike parental engagement), the school's offsetting effort reduction could substantially dampen the treatment effect at scale. If \u948  is small, the complementarity dominates and the treatment effect is amplified. Fu & Mehta's framework gives you the machinery to compute both scenarios and compare them to the reduced-form RCT estimate, which is exactly the kind of external validity argument your notes describe as the policy payoff of the structural approach.\
